You can use `CompletableFuture` for that.

    CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -&gt; {
        // Some time consuming computation
        return &quot;Result&quot;;
    }).thenAccept(result -&gt; {
        // This will be executed when the computation is done.
        System.out.println(result);
    });


`supplyAsync` starts a task in a separate thread that does some computation and returns a result. 
`thenAccept` is a callback that is called when the computation is finished, with the result of the computation as a parameter.

You can combine `@Async` with `CompletableFuture`:

    @Async
    public CompletableFuture&lt;String&gt; asyncMethod() {
        // Some time consuming task
        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(&quot;Result&quot;);
    }
    
    public void callerMethod() {
        asyncMethod().thenAccept(result -&gt; {
            // This will be executed when asyncMethod is done.
            System.out.println(result);
        });
    }
When you call `callerMethod()`, it will call `asyncMethod()`, which will be executed in a separate thread. The `thenAccept` callback will be called when `asyncMethod()` is finished, with the result of `asyncMethod()` as a parameter.

In your case, you can use a `CompletableFuture` that wraps the execution of your tasks and retrieves the value of the error counter when all tasks have finished. This can be achieved by using the `thenApply` or `thenAccept` methods of the `CompletableFuture`.

